    'DecisionTree': {

In [7]:
def plot_best_params(model_name, best_params, best_results):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    x_labels = []
    for params in best_params:
        label = ""
        if model_name == 'RandomForest':
            if 'n_estimators' in params:
                label += f"{params['n_estimators']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'criterion' in params:
                label += f"{params['criterion']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'max_depth' in params:
                label += f"{params['max_depth']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'max_features' in params:
                label += f"{params['max_features']}"
            else:
                label += "N/A"
        elif model_name == 'LogisticRegression':
            if 'C' in params:
                label += f"C={params['C']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'solver' in params:
                label += f"solver={params['solver']}"
            else:
                label += "N/A"
        elif model_name == 'KNeighbors':
            if 'n_neighbors' in params:
                label += f"n_neighbors={params['n_neighbors']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'weights' in params:
                label += f"weights={params['weights']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'metric' in params:
                label += f"metric={params['metric']}"
            else:
                label += "N/A"
        elif model_name == 'GradientBoosting':
            if 'n_estimators' in params:
                label += f"n_estimators={params['n_estimators']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'learning_rate' in params:
                label += f"learning_rate={params['learning_rate']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'max_depth' in params:
                label += f"max_depth={params['max_depth']}"
            else:
                label += "N/A"
        elif model_name == 'DecisionTree':
            if 'max_depth' in params:
                label += f"max_depth={params['max_depth']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'criterion' in params:
                label += f"criterion={params['criterion']}\n"
            else:
                label += "N/A\n"
            if 'splitter' in params:
                label += f"splitter={params['splitter']}"
            else:
                label += "N/A"

        x_labels.append(label)

    plt.plot(x_labels, [score for score, _ in best_results], marker='o', linestyle='-', color='green')
    plt.xlabel('Parameter Combinations')
    plt.ylabel('Average Cross Validation Score')
    plt.title(f'Top 5 Results for {model_name} Model')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

best_models = {}
best_scores = {}
all_results = []

for model_name in models:
    print(f"Optimizing {model_name} model...")
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=models[model_name], param_grid=param_grids[model_name], cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
    grid_search.fit(X, y)

    best_models[model_name] = grid_search.best_estimator_
    best_scores[model_name] = grid_search.best_score_

    with open(f'{model_name}_results.txt', 'w') as f:
        f.write(f"Best parameters for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_params_}\n")
        f.write(f"Best cross-validation score for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_score_}\n\n")
        print(f"Best parameters for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_params_}\n")
        print(f"Best cross-validation score for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_score_}\n\n")
        # Write all results
        for mean_score, params in zip(grid_search.cv_results_['mean_test_score'], grid_search.cv_results_['params']):
            f.write(f"Parameters: {params} | Average Cross-Validation Score: {mean_score}\n")

        # Parameters and scores of the best results
        results = list(zip(grid_search.cv_results_['mean_test_score'], grid_search.cv_results_['params']))
        results.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)  # Sort by scores
        best_results = results[:5]

        # Call the function for plotting
        plot_best_params(model_name, [params for _, params in best_results], best_results)

# Selecting the best model
best_model_name = max(best_scores, key=best_scores.get)
best_model = best_models[best_model_name]
best_params = grid_search.best_params_

In [11]:
# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)

# Initialize dictionaries to store best models and scores
best_models_pca = {}
best_scores_pca = {}

# Initialize list to store all results
all_results_pca = []

# Loop through each model
for model_name in models:
    print(f"Optimizing {model_name} with PCA...")
    
    # Perform Grid Search CV
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=models[model_name], param_grid=param_grids[model_name], cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
    grid_search.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)
    
    # Store best model and score
    best_models_pca[model_name] = grid_search.best_estimator_
    best_scores_pca[model_name] = grid_search.best_score_

    # Print and store results
    print(f"Best params for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_params_}")
    print(f"Best cross-validation score for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_score_}\n")
    results_str = f"Best params for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_params_}\nBest cross-validation score for {model_name}: {grid_search.best_score_}"
    all_results_pca.append(results_str)
    
    # Store results in a text file
    with open(f'{model_name}_resultswithpca.txt', 'w') as f:
        f.write(results_str + '\n')
        for mean_score, params in zip(grid_search.cv_results_['mean_test_score'], grid_search.cv_results_['params']):
            f.write(f"Parameters: {params} | Average Cross-Validation Score: {mean_score}\n")
        
        # Sort results by mean_test_score to get best 5 results
        results_sorted = sorted(zip(grid_search.cv_results_['mean_test_score'], grid_search.cv_results_['params']), key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)[:5]
        best_results_str = "\n".join([f"Parameters: {params} | Average Cross-Validation Score: {score}" for score, params in results_sorted])
        f.write(f"\nTop 5 Results:\n{best_results_str}\n\n")

    # Plot best parameters for the model
    plot_best_params(model_name, [params for _, params in results_sorted], results_sorted)

# Select the best model based on highest cross-validation score with PCA
best_model_name_pca = max(best_scores_pca, key=best_scores_pca.get)
best_model_pca = best_models_pca[best_model_name_pca]

# Print the best model and its cross-validation score with PCA
print(f"The best model with PCA is {best_model_name_pca} with a cross-validation score of {best_scores_pca[best_model_name_pca]}")

print(f"The best model with PCA is {best_model_name_pca} with a cross-validation score of {best_scores_pca[best_model_name_pca]}")

The best model without PCA is RandomForest with a cross-validation score of 0.7368896605485082
The best model with PCA is RandomForest with a cross-validation score of 0.7013529542590259

Hyperparameter Optimization:

we change in hyperparameters affected the training success and it was observed that more successful systems were obtained when the correct parameters were selected. Although the best parameters are different for each data set, if we talk about the currently used data set; The system is better at max_depth:30 concept: This may mean that the data is separate from each other. They may tend to be separate groups and may be more successful at higher depths. Considering the success of RandomForest, it seems that it is easier to adapt to algorithms with Tree logic such as ExtraTree...

PCA

PCA caused loss of success for this data set in my experiments, but this does not mean that PCA will cause you to lose success every time. You can see that it increases your success in other data sets as well. From another perspective, it was observed that the data analysis and processing time was shortened due to the smaller data set (due to the use of PCA). .
